				<figure class="wp-block-image alignfull size-large"><img width="683" height="1024" decoding="async" src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%20683%201024'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="shredded tofu bulgogi rice bowl" class="wp-image-20917" data-lazy-src="https://thefoodietakesflight.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/Shredded-Tofu-Bulgogi-Bowl-7-of-8-683x1024.jpg"><noscript><img width="683" height="1024" decoding="async" loading="lazy" src="https://thefoodietakesflight.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/Shredded-Tofu-Bulgogi-Bowl-7-of-8-683x1024.jpg" alt="shredded tofu bulgogi rice bowl" class="wp-image-20917"></noscript></figure>



<p>Shredding tofu and baking or air-frying it to draw out excess moisture creates a unique texture that almost resembles ground meat. This shredded tofu bulgogi bowl is cooked down in a sauce that’s spicy, savoury, a little sweet, and oh-so flavourful. It’s a delicious tofu recipe you can prepare to serve over rice.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image alignfull size-large"><img width="683" height="1024" decoding="async" src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%20683%201024'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="A bowl with rice and shredded tofu bulgogi plus sliced green onions" class="wp-image-33828" data-lazy-src="https://thefoodietakesflight.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/Shredded-Tofu-Bulgogi-Recipe-2-of-5-1-683x1024.jpg"><noscript><img width="683" height="1024" decoding="async" loading="lazy" src="https://thefoodietakesflight.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/Shredded-Tofu-Bulgogi-Recipe-2-of-5-1-683x1024.jpg" alt="A bowl with rice and shredded tofu bulgogi plus sliced green onions" class="wp-image-33828"></noscript></figure>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="ftf-what-kind-of-tofu-is-best-to-use">WHAT KIND OF TOFU IS BEST TO USE? </h2>



<p>Using extra firm tofu or tokwa is key for this recipe. There are types of extra firm tofu that come pre-pressed and in vacuum-sealed pouches that are great because they're really super firm and hold up well.</p>



<p>Firm tofu might work too but it can easily crumble. Silken or soft tofu will most definitely not work since it won’t be able to hold up when shredded.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image alignfull size-large"><img width="588" height="1024" decoding="async" src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%20588%201024'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="extra firm tofu block" class="wp-image-20920" data-lazy-src="https://thefoodietakesflight.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/Shredded-Tofu-Bulgogi-Bowl-8-of-24-588x1024.jpg"><noscript><img width="588" height="1024" decoding="async" loading="lazy" src="https://thefoodietakesflight.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/Shredded-Tofu-Bulgogi-Bowl-8-of-24-588x1024.jpg" alt="extra firm tofu block" class="wp-image-20920"></noscript></figure>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="ftf-shredded-tofu">SHREDDED TOFU</h2>



<p>I first stumbled upon this shredded tofu technique on Tiktok and don’t recall exactly whose video i saw but was really intrigued and decided to give it a try. I love how the tofu comes out almost like minced meat, texture-wise, since baking or air frying it really draws out extra moisture from the tofu.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image alignfull size-large"><img width="588" height="1024" decoding="async" src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%20588%201024'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="shredded extra firm tofu" class="wp-image-20924" data-lazy-src="https://thefoodietakesflight.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/Shredded-Tofu-Bulgogi-Bowl-12-of-24-588x1024.jpg"><noscript><img width="588" height="1024" decoding="async" loading="lazy" src="https://thefoodietakesflight.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/Shredded-Tofu-Bulgogi-Bowl-12-of-24-588x1024.jpg" alt="shredded extra firm tofu" class="wp-image-20924"></noscript></figure>



<p>I cooked mine until golden brown and crisp on the edges while some pieces are still white and soft so when you add everything together, you get a really nice mix of textures.</p>



<p>The shredded tofu itself is a great vessel for any kind of sauce or marinade you like but I opted for a bulgogi style sauce.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image alignfull size-large"><img width="588" height="1024" decoding="async" src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%20588%201024'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="" class="wp-image-20910" data-lazy-src="https://thefoodietakesflight.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/Shredded-Tofu-Bulgogi-Bowl-3-of-24-588x1024.jpg"><noscript><img width="588" height="1024" decoding="async" loading="lazy" src="https://thefoodietakesflight.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/Shredded-Tofu-Bulgogi-Bowl-3-of-24-588x1024.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-20910"></noscript></figure>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="ftf-bulgogi-sauce">BULGOGI SAUCE</h2>



<p>This bulgogi sauce is inspired by Korean bulgogi. I love to use gochujang because of its distinct heat with a nice hint of sweetness and of course it’s umami. It’s also thick so helps bring the sauce together. </p>



<figure class="wp-block-image alignfull size-large"><img width="588" height="1024" decoding="async" src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%20588%201024'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="bulgogi sauce" class="wp-image-20918" data-lazy-src="https://thefoodietakesflight.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/Shredded-Tofu-Bulgogi-Bowl-7-of-24-588x1024.jpg"><noscript><img width="588" height="1024" decoding="async" loading="lazy" src="https://thefoodietakesflight.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/Shredded-Tofu-Bulgogi-Bowl-7-of-24-588x1024.jpg" alt="bulgogi sauce" class="wp-image-20918"></noscript></figure>



<p>I added some grated Asian pear (grated Fuji apple works amazing too) for extra sweetness to the sauce.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image alignfull size-large"><img width="1024" height="683" decoding="async" src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%201024%20683'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="A bowl with rice and shredded tofu bulgogi plus sliced green onions" class="wp-image-33829" data-lazy-src="https://thefoodietakesflight.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/Shredded-Tofu-Bulgogi-Recipe-3-of-5-1-1024x683.jpg"><noscript><img width="1024" height="683" decoding="async" loading="lazy" src="https://thefoodietakesflight.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/Shredded-Tofu-Bulgogi-Recipe-3-of-5-1-1024x683.jpg" alt="A bowl with rice and shredded tofu bulgogi plus sliced green onions" class="wp-image-33829"></noscript></figure>



